Step 2: Therefore, there exists a scalar $\alpha$ such that $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c} = \alpha \mathbf{b}.$
This can be written as an equation:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ - 3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} &= \alpha \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \\[4pt]
\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} \alpha \\ \alpha \\ \alpha \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}
Since $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c} = \alpha \mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0,$ we have $(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c}) \cdot \mathbf{a} = \alpha (\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}).$
\begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} \alpha \\ \alpha \\ \alpha \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} &= 0 \\ 2 \alpha + \alpha &= 0 \\ 3 \alpha &= 0 \\ \alpha &= 0 \end{align*}
Since $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c} = \alpha \mathbf{b}$ and $\alpha = 0,$ we have $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c} = \mathbf{0}.$  Therefore, $\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{c}.$
